        <h5>
            <a href="http://www.amazon.com/Who-Wrote-New-Testament-ebook/dp/B00APGJZSC">Who Wrote the New Testament?: The Making of the Christian Myth</a>
        </h5>

        <p>
            <br>
        </p>

        <p>
            <span>​In this groundbreaking and controversial book, Burton Mack brilliantly exposes how the Gospels are fictional mythologies created by different communities for various purposes and are only distantly related to the actual historical Jesus. A comprehensive synthesis of New Tes</span>
            <span>tament scholarship that is nevertheless popularly accessible, it will make a particularly useful introductory text in an area where such texts are in great demand. As the subtitle suggests, the book is also a critical account of the making of the Christian myth--an invitation to critical reflection on the social construction of a foundational epic that has shaped (and been shaped by) the history and behavior of the West since Constantine. Whether Jesus actually lived is insignificant beside how stories of his life and ideas were promulgated. Mack carefully depicts the socio-political scenario in which the Jesus story took root.</span>
        </p>

